Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the White House of Trump is taking over the Statue of Liberty
The safest sign of a regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
The Americans appreciate this as well as any other - hence the carefully staged fall of Saddam Hussein at Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe in a heated dispute with Jim Acosta of CNN about the president’s proposals for drastically restricting legal immigration to the Statue of Liberty.
To remain fair, Miller did not attack the statue himself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had.
But he seized its importance, and in particular the importance attributed to it, when the famous poem of Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument.
As Miller Acosta once said, “I don’t want to go into a complete thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem to which you refer, which was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller is factually correct, but as he himself put it, it’s not really about history.
It’s about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only one in which a state not only invites some old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: “Your tiredness, your poor, your oppressed masses, who long to breathe freely, the miserable waste of your rich coasts.”
There has never been a time when the “wrong waste” on our screens could be seen better.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people in Trump's U.S. are not welcome.
This conflict because of the importance of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural dispute: it is indeed a conflict about the importance of America.
Lazarus – and her friends, who were committed to placing their words at the base after her death – knew very well that they were doing a highly political action.
The sculpture was intended to show the links between French and American republicanism by portraying in a worn-out classical pictorial representation the female embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: the mother of exiles.
The combination of the poem with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the significance of the statue, people from the right wing wanted to change this back for a long time.
The great shrewd Rush Limbaugh, a type of John the Baptist for Trump’s coming, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative who brings the American flame into the night-time world: “Lady Liberty is moving forward.
It is intended to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch should not illuminate the path to the United States."
Quite unusually, Limbaugh has come across something here.
The significance of the statue is entirely a question of the point of view of perception.
Lazarus’ great act of imagination was to see it as it was seen by the exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
In the truest sense, it is about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they must hear.
And of course, that’s not the perspective Miller and Trump ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch should not illuminate the way, but ignite hatred, which is their only source of power.
