New Results of Swedish Asylum Age Assessment Tests Released
Recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have been subjected to a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80 percent of the tested individuals are over the age of 18. But not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Agency for Forensic Medicine (R<0xC3><0xA4>ttsmedicinalverket) has started conducting the tests last year.
During the asylum process, they should make the assessment of the age more precise after the Swedish Migration Agency was criticized for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were underage.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years of age or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under the age of 18".
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent over the past few months.
“We don’t see a big difference in the statistics of the past months, the numbers are pretty constant,” he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases in which the person has been assessed as over 18 years of age does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker has lied about his age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases that “propose that the investigated person is 18 years of age or older.”
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, she found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly stated that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints are made, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think the type of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say it for sure, we shouldn't pretend we could," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "Generally speaking, you can say that the risk of judging a child wrong as an adult is low.
